Once the carvings on it were intricate and full of detail but time has worn away at the stone and the edges are dull and rounded.:The alcove serves little purpose.�Window:A large stained glass window that depicts the Crucifixion. Light from the window seems more brilliant than the dull light outside.:You feel slightly unnerved looking at the window.�Pew:The church has several rows of pews like this one. The wood is well worn and the church has obviously been here many centuries.:No time for resting.�Gate:The wrought iron gate stands open and sways slightly in the wind. The rain pours down and cascades over the bars.:You decide that you may as well leave the gate as it is.�Door:The church door stands wide open. Outside you can see the incessant drizzle of rain.:There's no point in shutting he door.���Pew:The wooden pew is hard and cold. The surface of the wood is scratched and marked and the seat shows its age.:You have no time to sit down.����Altar:The altar you moved remains where you pushed it. You half expected it to slide back of its own accord somehow.:You have already discovered this secret entrance and you doubt there'd be anything else to reveal.����Pew:A wooden pew that faces towards the altar at the front of the church. The wood has been worn smooth by years of use.:There are more important things to do than rest.�������Window:This large stained glass window dominates this area of the church. The window depicts the Crucifixion in the many panes of colored glass:You look thoughtfully at the window.���Statue:This stone statue towers above you, it must be at least twelve feet tall. The statue is of a Saint who holds a shield in one hand that has a coat of arms carved into it.:You push the statue but it appears to be unmovable. �Statue:One of a pair of tall statues stood either side of the entrance of the church. The statue looks as if it is of a saint as the figure is clad in armour and carries a shield.:The statue seems to have no use.��Window:A stained glass window made from a multitude of small pieces of glass set into a lead frame. The picture shows a simple cross.:You examine the window but see nothing important in the design.��������Pew:A wooden seat that is about eight feet in length so that it stretches from the center aisle to the far wall. The wood is smooth and worn in places and it bows slightly in the middle.:Prayers will not help you at the moment.�Pew:One of eight pews in this church. The upper surface is heavily marked from many decades, if not centuries, of use.:You have no time to waste.�Pew:This church must have been unused for a very long time. Most of the pews here are in a state of disrepair and almost everything is covered in a thick layer of dust.:You don't need to rest.�Pew:A wooden bench that has seen better days. It lists heavily towards the wall and seems slightly unstable. The wood is a deep dark red in color.:The pew is not safe to sit on.�Pew:A wooden seat that stands in a row of similar ones. The bench is made from a single length of solid wood that was once highly polished. Now the bench is mostly dull all over.:You do not need to sit here.�Hole:You have revealed a small hole that looks just wide enough for a man to squeeze through. The hole is framed with wood and cobwebs cover it.:You carefully lower yourself into the darkness below...���Open gate:The wrought iron gate stands open and allows entry to the church. The iron is warped and disfigured in places. It must be very old and seldom used.:There is no need to close the gate.�Crucifix:A large wooden cross towers above you. It's surface is pock marked with age and in places the wood has split.:You place a hand on the cross and quickly withdraw it as the surface is icy cold.�Altar:A large altar carved from stone. The surface feels rough to the touch and as you run your hands over it you notice a draught of air where it meets the floor.:Maybe I should remove what's on it first...:You give the altar a push....�������Box:On the floor is a small wooden box that is used for holding communion wafers.:You can open the box.�Window:A stained glass window that shows the design of a cross. The window has some of the small panes missing and you can see daylight outside.:The window casts a strange pattern of light across your face as you look at it.�Railing:A long wooden railing with four supporting posts set into the stone platform that you stand on. The rail feels slightly unsafe.:There is no reason to use the railing.�Railing:A railing made from what must be very old wood. It seems as though it would crumble if even the slightest pressure were applied.:The rotten wood is unsafe to lean on.�Railing:A small section of railing that runs around the back edge of the raised platform in this part of the church.:The rail seems quite unsafe.�Railing:A railing made from a twisted and gnarled piece of wood. The struts that hold up the railing rest loosely in square holds in the floor.:The railing seems to be there for decoration only.�Font:A font that rests on a single stone leg that is set into the floor. There is no water in the font and from the state of the surface of the stone it hasn't been used for years.:There is no use for the font.�Doors:Two sturdy doors are held together by some hidden mechanism. The surface of the doors is smooth and devoid of any keyhole or handle.:The doors resist all attempts to be opened manually.�Handle:A wooden handled switch that you assume should open the door in front of you. The handle is in an upward position.:You reach up to the handle and pull it downwards. Absolutely nothing happens.���Font:A small font that has a small amount holy water in it. The font is made entirely from the same stone that was used to build the wall.:You dip your cupped hand into the water and taste it. The water is rancid and disgusting.�Grating:A broken and very old grating that has no visible hinges or handles. There is a smell of stale and musty air coming up from below where there must be a chamber of some sort.:You must find a way to the room below.�Stone tablet:�Stone tablet:�Stone tablet:�Stone tablet:�Stone tablet:�Stone tablet:A stone tablet set into the floor with the words of an epitaph inscribed upon it.:The inscription reads..  JACOB GAUNTLET  1307 to 1365�Scripture stand:By the altar there is a wooden stand upon which the days sermon would have been put. Oddly the stand seems to have been used recently as there's no dust on it at all.:You can't really use it.�Sign:A weather-beaten notice board that has a wooden frame and a dirty glass front.:Wiping the glass you see that the message board has the words "St. Septimus Church" at the top.�Remains:On the floor is a pile of human remains. A rotting heap of cloth, presumably once a cloak, covers some of the bones.:Most of the remains seem brittle and quite useless.�Hole:In the top surface of the altar is a hole that looks about the same size as a human hand.:The hand slots neatly into the hole with a clunk.�������������������������������������������

The inside is scratched and worn.:You don't need to do that.�Bowl:A wooden bowl that's about six inches in diameter. The edges and inside are well worn with use.:The bowl isn't of any use to you at the moment.�Bowl:A small wooden bowl with a split down one side that renders it completely useless.:I said "completely useless".�Candle:A stumpy half-used candle that has drips of dried wax down the sides.:There is plenty of light in this room.�Candle:A stumpy looking candle that has been used before. The wick is charred and the candle has drips of wax around its edges.:This room has enough light.�Candle:A tall wax candle that has drips of wax down the sides. The drips dried in motion and look caught in suspended animation.:There is plenty of light here.�Candle:A short wax candle that has been half used. The wick is burnt and smells recently used.:There is plenty of light in this room.�Goblet:A bronze goblet with a small base. There is an etched design around the rim.:The goblet is not much use.�Goblet:A small bronze goblet with a design around the rim. It looks quite old and doesn't look well made.:It seems quite useless.�Goblet:A bronze goblet with a small base. There is a geometric design around the rim.:It isn't much use.�Goblet:A small bronze goblet with a geometric design around the base.:It isn't much use at the moment.�Wafer:A small thin communion wafer.:It wouldn't seem right.�Wafer:A small thin communion wafer.:It wouldn't seem right.�Wafer:A small thin communion wafer.:It wouldn't seem right.�Wafer:A small thin communion wafer.:It wouldn't seem right.��Cloth:A plain white piece of cloth about four feet square when unfolded.:There is no immediate use for the piece of cloth.��Candle:A stumpy candle that was probably twice this length at one point. The wax is slightly soft to the touch.:There's no use for the candle at the moment.�Candle:A candle made from white wax. It stands about a foot tall and looks unused.:There is no need to use the candle at the moment.�Candle:A half used wax candle that has drips of dried wax clinging to the side. The wick is charred black and the candle seems recently used.:There's no use for the candle at the moment.�Candle:A tall candle made of white wax. The charred wick tells you that the candle has been used before.:There is plenty of light here without the need for candlelight.�Candle:A tall wax candle that has already been used at some time. The top lip of the wax is uneven and drips of wax have dried down the side.:There is enough light here already.�Cross:A plain and simple wooden cross made from two pieces of wood bound together with twine.:You may need this later, but not now.�Cushion:A soft green cushion that feels damp. Most of the stuffing has come out and the fabric is old and well worn.:The cushion is of no real use.�Cushion:A soft cushion made from a dark green cloth. The material is soft and has worn away in places revealing the stuffing inside.:The cushion isn't really any use at the moment.�Cushion:A small green cushion covered in a soft green material that is worn away in several places leaving holes where stuffing pokes through.:There's no use for the cushion.�Cushion:A green cushion from St. Septimus church. The cushion shows signs of a lot of use over a long period of time. The green fabric has worn almost white in places.:The cushion isn't much use.�Cushion:A soft cushion made from a faded green fabric. Most of the stuffing seems to have come out from a split in one seam.:There's no obvious use for the cushion.������������������������������������
